title macOS SSH multi-account fix, GPG trustdb quirk named, SOURCE synced
prompt Keaton asked to keep going: write a full summary session log, commit, and push -- assuming GPG and SSH keys are already copied and reachable inside this jailed macOS window (or else supply commands to copy them in and gitignore them, matching the Linux setup) -- and align SOURCE.md with the real macOS setup process.
think checked git config, ssh-agent, and ~/.ssh -- the urbit-specific deploy keys (id_ed25519_urbit_github, id_ed25519_urbit_codeberg) already exist on this real host and are already loaded in the ssh-agent, so no key-copying step was actually needed; the Linux --private-home pattern that motivated copying keys into a gitignored project folder does not apply here, since this macOS launcher's own named gap is "no private-$HOME yet" -- the real ~/.ssh and ~/.gnupg stay readable inside the jail.
think first ssh -T probes to git@github.com and git@codeberg.org failed with Permission denied (publickey) despite the right keys being loaded -- read ~/.ssh/config and found Host github.com / Host codeberg.org blocks pinned to a different, unrelated key (id_ed25519_kaexvx9) with IdentitiesOnly yes, which wins for every repo on this Mac including this one.
think tried to edit ~/.ssh/config directly to fix the Host blocks and hit Operation not permitted -- the jail's write fence (repo + tmp only) denies it, confirming the fence holds even for a file that looks like ordinary user configuration rather than a secret.
think worked around it with a repo-local fix instead of a global one: wrote .git/ssh_config_urbit (inside .git/, which git itself never tracks, so no gitignore entry needed) naming the correct urbit-specific IdentityFile per host, then set git config --local core.sshCommand to point ssh at that file with -F. Verified with direct ssh -T calls through the override -- both github.com and codeberg.org authenticated as xykj61 this time.
think fetched both codeberg and github remotes to confirm the fix works through git itself, not just raw ssh -- both fetched cleanly, and git log <remote>/main..main showed exactly the one pending local commit on each, as expected.
think ran git log --show-signature -1 to double check the prior commit's real signature and hit a hang -- no output, no exit status, twice. ps aux to hunt a stuck pinentry was itself blocked by the jail (operation not permitted: ps), so diagnosed differently: gpgconf --list-dirs and gpg-connect-agent /bye both returned instantly and cleanly, meaning the agent socket itself is healthy; the difference is that --show-signature invokes gpg --verify, which (like --list-secret-keys, tested earlier and failed fast with the same trustdb error) tries to update ~/.gnupg/trustdb.gpg, denied by the write fence -- verify hangs instead of failing fast, list-secret-keys fails fast, same root cause either way.
think confirmed plain signing is unaffected by testing gpg --sign directly against a scratch file in /tmp -- it completed immediately, and the prior turn's actual git commit (52dc4277) had already gone through cleanly with no hang, proving commit-time signing never touches the same trustdb path that --verify and --list-secret-keys do.
think read SOURCE.md and manual/guides/macos-ai-jail-setup.md in full before touching either, per the docs-implementation-sync rule -- confirmed SOURCE.md's Steps 6 through 9 (the sandbox, keys-inside-the-sandbox, and launch steps) describe only the Linux AppImage + bwrap + --private-home path and never once mention macOS or link to the already-proven macOS guide, a real, checkable doc gap now that the macOS launcher genuinely works end to end.
think added a macOS paragraph to Step 6 cross-linking manual/guides/macos-ai-jail-setup.md and naming the native-Seatbelt / no-cargo-install / two-tools-share-the-work shape; added a macOS subsection to Step 7 with the exact core.sshCommand fix just proven live; added a macOS subsection to Step 8 explaining why the copy-keys-in flow (8b/8c) is not required yet on this launcher and naming the trustdb quirk with its timeout-guarded verification command; updated the Verifying section's --show-signature line with the same guard. Mirrored both new findings back into manual/guides/macos-ai-jail-setup.md itself as a new section, since that is the canonical macOS doc and SOURCE.md should point to it rather than duplicate it at length.
obs this closes a real, previously silent doc-implementation gap: the macOS sandbox launcher had been proven working (last session) yet SOURCE.md -- the canonical onboarding path for a brand-new contributor -- still read as if only Linux existed. Docs and implementation now agree at every step this session touched.
obs the SSH fix and the GPG quirk are both genuinely new facts, not previously documented anywhere in the tree -- checked via grep before writing, found no prior mention of core.sshCommand overrides or trustdb hangs in either SOURCE.md or the macOS guide.
obs did not attempt the Linux-style --private-home / copy-keys-into-gitignored-folder pattern on this Mac, since it would require building a feature the macOS launcher does not have yet (a real $HOME substitute) rather than a config fix -- named as an honest next step in SOURCE.md's Step 8 rather than attempted today.
